To explain this without a lambda, we have to look at what Java is doing "under the hood."
A Lambda is just a shorthand way of creating an Anonymous Inner Class. Before lambdas existed (pre-Java 8), we had to write out the full class definition every time we wanted to pass a "task" to a thread.
1. The "Manual" Way (Creating a Task Class)
To avoid the lambda, we create a small class that implements the Callable interface. This class "holds" the data (the batch) until a thread is ready to process it.
// This is what the Lambda was doing for you automatically

class SalesforceTask implements Callable<List<SyncResult>> {
    private final List<SalesforceRecord> batch;
    private final SalesforceIntegrationService service;

    // Constructor to "capture" the data and the service
    public SalesforceTask(List<SalesforceRecord> batch, SalesforceIntegrationService service) {
        this.batch = batch;
        this.service = service;
    }

    @Override
    public List<SyncResult> call() throws Exception {
        // This is the actual work that will run inside the Virtual Thread
        return service.pushBatchToSalesforce(batch);
    }
}

2. The Simplified "Orchestrator" (Without Streams or Lambdas)
Now, instead of that complex .stream().map(...) line, we use a simple for loop to create these task objects.
public List<SyncResult> processInParallel(List<SalesforceRecord> allRecords) {
    // 1. Partition the data using Guava
    List<List<SalesforceRecord>> batches = Lists.partition(allRecords, 200);

    // 2. Create a list to hold our "Tasks"
    List<Callable<List<SyncResult>>> tasks = new ArrayList<>();

    // 3. Loop through batches and create a new Task object for each one
    for (List<SalesforceRecord> batch : batches) {
        // We create an instance of our class and pass in the data
        SalesforceTask task = new SalesforceTask(batch, this.salesforceService);
        tasks.add(task);
    }

    // 4. Hand the list of tasks to the Virtual Thread Executor
    try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
        List<Future<List<SyncResult>>> futures = executor.invokeAll(tasks);
        
        // ... gather results from futures as before ...
    } catch (Exception e) {
        throw new RuntimeException(e);
    }
}

Why the Lambda is usually preferred
When you see batch -> () -> service.push(batch), Java is essentially doing all that "Class," "Constructor," and "Override" boilerplate for you behind the scenes.
 * The Lambda version: Focuses on what to do (service.push(batch)).
 * The Class version: Focuses on how to build the object to hold the data.
Summary of the Flow
 * The Batch: You have the data.
 * The Task (Callable): You wrap the data and the instruction into a "package."
 * The Executor: You give the "package" to a Virtual Thread.
 * The Future: The Executor gives you a receipt (the Future) while it works.
